\par
  1. Lock the hook before you write anything\par
  A series lives or dies on its hook. Spend a weekend deciding these four things together:\par
  - The world rule \f2\emdash  what's the one weird thing that makes mushroom-folk different from regular fairy-tale creatures? (e.g. they remember everything that ever grew where they stand; they can only speak when it\par
   rains; each mushroom child inherits a single memory from the forest)\par
  - The recurring problem \emdash  what do they struggle with in every book? (belonging, change, being small in a big world \emdash  your girlfriend's caregiving lens is gold here)\par
  - The cast anchor \emdash  2-3 core characters who appear in every book, plus a rotating guest per story\par
  - The signature visual \emdash  one thing YOUR art does that nobody else's mushroom book does. Pick it on purpose.\par
  The hook should be sayable in one sentence. "Paddington is a bear from Peru who lives with a London family." Do that for Mooshu.\par
  2. Pick your KDP format strategically\par
  For zero capital, start with:\par
  - 6\f0\'d79 or 8\'d78 paperback picture book (KDP's cheapest trim that still looks like a real picture book)\par
  - Kindle version with fixed-layout for the illustrations\par
  - Skip hardcover until book 2 or 3 proves demand\par
  First book target: 24\f2\endash 32 interior pages, ~300\endash 500 words. Short enough to finish, long enough to feel real.\par
  3. Divide the work by strength\par
  - You (artist): character sheets \f3\u8594?\f0  storyboard thumbnails \f3\u8594?\f0  final illustrations \f3\u8594?\f0  cover \f3\u8594?\f0  KDP interior layout\par
  - Her (caregiver/creative): story structure, dialogue, read-aloud testing with actual kids she works with (huge unfair advantage \f2\emdash  use it), back-cover copy\par
  - Shared: the hook, character decisions, brand voice\par
  Her testing stories on real kids before you illustrate is the single biggest edge you have over other KDP authors.\par
  4. Build the brand in public, for free\par
  Start a single Instagram or TikTok account before book 1 launches. Post:\par
  - Character design process\par
  - Sketches, timelapses, "meet the mushroom" intros\par
  - Her reading drafts to kids (with permission) and their reactions\par
  You're not selling a book, you're building an audience that wants book 1 when it drops. 60\endash 90 days of posting before launch is realistic.\par
  5. Launch sequence for book 1\par
  1. Finish book + get 3\endash 5 beta readers (parents, teachers, librarians in her network)\par
  2. Order 1 author proof from KDP (~$5) to check print quality\par
  3. Publish paperback + Kindle same day\par
  4. Price paperback at KDP minimum + $1\endash 2, Kindle at $2.99 or $3.99\par
  5. Ask your launch-week audience to buy + leave honest reviews (never pay for reviews \emdash  KDP bans accounts for it)\par
  6. Run a free Kindle promo day 30 to juice rankings\par
  6. Reinvest, don't invest\par
  First profits go into:\par
  - ISBNs if you want broader distribution (optional \emdash  KDP gives free ones)\par
  - A real domain + simple Squarespace/Carrd later\par
  - Maybe one paid Amazon ad experiment at $5/day once you have 2\endash 3 books\par
  Don't spend on: editors (swap with other indie authors), fancy software (Procreate + Affinity/Canva is enough), courses, or "KDP gurus."\par
  7. Cadence that won't burn you out\par
  One book every 3\endash 4 months for year one = 3\endash 4 books by end of year. A series needs volume to get discovered \emdash  single books get buried. Plan books 1\endash 4 together so foreshadowing and world-building compound.\par
