  4. Real indie examples at your level\par
  These are people who started roughly where you are and whose paths you can actually emulate:\par
  - Brigitte Brulz \emdash  self-publishes on KDP, markets virtually for free, works with her own daughter. Closest template to your setup.\par
  - Karen Inglis \emdash  The Secret Lake sold 500k+ copies as indie and got translated into 10 languages. She started unknown. Long game.\par
  - Darcy Pattison \emdash  left trad publishing for indie, now has 20+ titles. Example of what "series compounding" looks like after several years.\par
  - "Monty" series author \emdash  used Canva (zero expensive software) and won 5 awards across two self-published books. Proves tool cost is not the limit; craft + consistency are.\par
  - Shelby Wilde / Scavenger Scout \emdash  documented case study of a KDP picture book launch with real numbers.\par
  Common thread across all of them: they all committed to a series, not single books, and they all marketed the brand, not the book. That's exactly the posture Mooshu Books needs from day one.\par
  ---\par
\f1\u9679?\f4  This is the best version yet. The "stuck-above-ground because they haven't found their purpose" flip is genuinely strong \emdash  it's metaphorical enough to carry real meaning, simple enough that a 4-year-old\par
  reads it as "finding your special thing," and honest enough that you two will mean it when you write it. That authenticity shows on the page. Let's build it.\par
  ---\par
  MOOSHU BOOKS \emdash  Series Bible v1\par
  \u9632? World Rule (the unbreakable law)\par
  Every mushroom grows from a spore to do one thing, and when it's done, it returns to spores and drifts back into the forest. But sometimes a mushroom wakes up and doesn't know what they're for yet \emdash  and those ones stay. Those ones are the Mooshus.\par
  Sub-rules (internal consistency you'll need for plotting):\par
  - Mooshus can't force their purpose \emdash  they find it by noticing something the forest needs\par
  - When a Mooshu helps with the right thing, they feel a warm hum (their "knowing")\par
  - A Mooshu can feel another Mooshu's hum when it happens \emdash  that's how they find each other\par
  - The forest is full of regular mushrooms doing their jobs quietly; the Mooshus are the only ones who talk, wonder, and wander\par
  - Nobody is stuck forever. But nobody is rushed, either.\par
  \u9632? Signature Refrain\par
  Opening bookend (every book):\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Some mushrooms wake up knowing.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Some mushrooms wake up wondering.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The Mooshus are the wonderers."\par
  Closing bookend (every book):\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Not yet. Not yet. But a little more knowing than yesterday."\par
  This closing line does the heavy lifting. It's the emotional promise \emdash  progress without pressure. Parents with ADHD kids (or who have ADHD themselves) will feel it. Kids will chant "not yet, not yet" because the repetition is satisfying.\par
  \u9632? Emotional Promise\par
  "You don't have to know yet. You're still becoming."\par
  This is the whole series in one sentence. It's what a parent hands a kid when the kid feels small, scattered, left-behind, or unsure.\par
  \u9632? Core Cast (the three Mooshus)\par
  Three Mooshus, each carrying a different flavor of the "stuck" feeling. Together they're one whole kid.\par
  \f6\u-10180?\u-8380?\f4  MOOSHU (the protagonist \emdash  the Scatterer)\par
  - Visual: tiny, round pink-orange cap with white freckles, slightly tilted. Cap a little too big for her stem. Always looks like she just got somewhere.\par
  - Age-equivalent: 4\par
  - Wants: to try everything so she can find her thing\par
  - Fears: that her thing doesn't exist, or that she already missed it\par
  - Habit: starts projects mid-sentence, forgets them mid-sentence, remembers them three pages later\par
  - Signature phrase: "Maybe it's THIS one!" (said on page 2 of every book about something that turns out to not be it)\par
  - What she's actually for (series reveal): Mooshu's purpose is noticing \emdash  she sees what others miss because she's paying attention to everything at once. (That's the ADHD reframe, baked in.)\par
  \f6\u-10180?\u-8380?\f4  POPPEN (the steady one \emdash  the Waiter)\par
  - Visual: taller, soft tan cap that droops slightly on one side. Quiet eyes.\par
  - Age-equivalent: 5\par
  - Wants: to do it right when he finds it\par
  - Fears: picking wrong and wasting his one chance\par
  - Habit: sits very still and watches. Says important things quietly.\par
  - Signature phrase: "I'll know when I know."\par
  - What he's actually for: Poppen's purpose is steadying \emdash  being the ground other Mooshus stand on while they figure themselves out.\par
  \f6\u-10180?\u-8380?\f4  FIDDLE (the wild one \emdash  the Tryer)\par
  - Visual: tall curly stem, bright yellow cap with ragged edges, always mid-motion\par
  - Age-equivalent: 3\par
  - Wants: to do (any of it, all of it, now)\par
  - Fears: stopping long enough to feel stuck\par
  - Habit: answers questions before hearing them; sings instead of talks\par
  - Signature phrase: "I bet I can!" (followed immediately by trying and failing cheerfully)\par
  - What she's actually for: Fiddle's purpose is beginning \emdash  she's the one who starts things the others are too careful to start.\par
  The reveal the series is secretly building toward\par
  Their purposes only work together. Fiddle starts. Mooshu notices. Poppen steadies. That's why they're stuck as individuals \emdash  their "job" is being a trio. None of them finds a solo purpose, and that's the\par
  point. Belonging is the purpose.\par
  \u9632? Setting\par
  The Slow Forest. A damp, mossy, in-between place where the sun comes through in patches. Three recurring locations:\par
  - The Ring \emdash  where the Mooshus sleep, a circle of old stones with moss pillows\par
  - The Edge \emdash  where the forest meets something unknown (different in each book)\par
  - The Old Log \emdash  the refuge, where they go when they feel too small\par
  \u9632? Visual Signature\par
  Decide these together, but some options to pick from:\par
  - Hand-painted gouache textures (warm, storybook, non-digital feel) \emdash  matches emotional weight\par
  - Limited palette: moss green, rain grey, mushroom pink, lantern yellow, bark brown (5 swatches, reusable across all books = brand recognition)\par
  - The ONE thing: every Mooshu has freckles that glow faintly when they're close to their purpose. Small, subtle, but present in every illustration. That's your signature visual cue. Kids will start looking for it.\par
  \u9632? Story Engine (how every book is built)\par
  Every Mooshu book follows this 5-beat structure:\par
  1. Morning at the Ring \emdash  opening refrain + a new day\par
  2. The Edge calls \emdash  something small is wrong just beyond the forest (this book's problem, usually brought by a guest character)\par
  3. Each Mooshu tries their instinct \emdash  Fiddle charges in, Poppen waits, Mooshu notices \emdash  they each fail in their signature way\par
  4. The accidental combo \emdash  they solve it together without meaning to\par
  5. Return to the Ring \emdash  closing refrain + freckles glow a little brighter than yesterday\par
  This structure is load-bearing: it's what lets you write 20 books without running out. The guest character slot generates infinite plots.\par
  \u9632? What Never Happens (guardrails)\par
  - No Mooshu ever "graduates" to spores within the series \emdash  the point is the becoming\par
  - No villains. The "problem" is always something small and fixable\par
  - No shouting, no scary stakes, no loss\par
  - Purposes are never announced by an authority figure \emdash  always discovered by noticing\par
  - Humans never appear\par
  - Nobody is ever told they're doing it wrong\par
  \u9632? Five-Book Arc\par
  Each book is standalone (for new readers) but the trio deepens across the arc.\par
  Book 1 \emdash  "Mooshu Wakes Up Wondering"\par
  Pilot. Establishes the world, the three Mooshus, the refrain.\par
  - Guest: a beetle who's lost the path home\par
  - Problem: beetle can't remember which way the Ring is\par
  - What each tries: Fiddle runs off in a random direction / Poppen waits for beetle to remember / Mooshu notices beetle's footprints\par
  - Resolution: they follow the footprints backward together\par
  - Purpose-nudge: Mooshu discovers she's good at noticing\par
  Book 2 \emdash  "Poppen and the Waiting Tree"\par
  Poppen's spotlight.\par
  - Guest: a seedling that won't sprout\par
  - Problem: it's scared to grow\par
  - What each tries: Fiddle sings at it / Mooshu notices it's in a cold spot / Poppen just sits next to it, for a long time\par
  - Resolution: Poppen's quiet presence is what the seedling needs\par
  - Purpose-nudge: Poppen discovers steadying is a real thing to be good at\par
  Book 3 \emdash  "Fiddle Starts Something"\par
  Fiddle's spotlight.\par
  - Guest: a whole chorus of crickets who've forgotten how to begin their song\par
  - Problem: every cricket is waiting for another cricket to start\par
  - What each tries: Poppen waits with them (makes it worse) / Mooshu notices they're all looking at each other / Fiddle just chirps, badly, loudly, first\par
  - Resolution: Fiddle's bad first note gives everyone permission\par
  - Purpose-nudge: Fiddle discovers beginning is a gift\par
  Book 4 \emdash  "The Mooshu Who Tried to Leave"\par
  The wobble book. Emotional peak of the arc.\par
  - Guest: a new Mooshu, Piko, who wakes up at the Edge alone and wants to find her purpose by herself\par
  - Problem: Piko keeps trying solo, keeps failing, gets smaller and quieter\par
  - What each tries: all three try to help individually and fail\par
  - Resolution: they show up together without saying anything, and Piko's freckles glow\par
  - Purpose-nudge: the trio realizes their purposes only work together \emdash  this is the arc reveal, done gently, not announced\par
  - This is the book that will make parents cry. Write it carefully.\par
  Book 5 \emdash  "A Little More Knowing"\par
  The breath-out book. Quieter, celebratory.\par
  - Guest: none \emdash  the forest itself\par
  - Problem: nothing is wrong. Mooshu wakes up and realizes she's not panicked about her purpose anymore\par
  - What happens: a gentle day. Small moments. The three of them doing their things side-by-side\par
  - Resolution: no resolution needed. Just being.\par
  - Purpose-nudge: the closing refrain lands differently this time \emdash  "a little more knowing than yesterday" is now a whole year of yesterdays\par
  This is your series promise fulfilled. Book 6 onward can expand the cast (Piko joins, more Mooshus wake up) without breaking the structure.\par
  \u9632? Merch / IP Levers (notice, don't build yet)\par
  - Most plushie-able: Fiddle (wild, colorful, active poses)\par
  - Most print-able scene: the Ring at dawn with all three sleeping\par
  - Most t-shirt-able phrase: "Not yet. Not yet." or "The wonderers."\par
  - Signature recurring motif for merch: the glowing freckles\par
\par
 Mooshu Books \emdash  The Slow Forest Bible\par
  (a living document \emdash  add, trim, re-word; it should sound like you two by the end)\par
  ---\par
  The world, in its own voice\par
  In the Slow Forest, every mushroom grows for a reason. A spore drifts, lands, wakes, does its small quiet thing, and when the thing is done, it lets itself go again \emdash  soft, without fuss, back into the drifting.\par
  Most mushrooms know their reason the moment they wake.\par
  The Mooshus don't.\par
  The Mooshus are the ones who wake up wondering. Who sit up in the moss and look around and can't quite remember what they're for. So they stay. They don't go back into the drifting, because they haven't done their one thing yet, and a mushroom can't rest until it has.\par
  Nobody rushes them. The forest is patient. The rain comes and goes. The Mooshus wonder, and wander, and little by little they notice.\par
  ---\par
  The feeling we want to hand a kid\par
  You don't have to know yet. You're still becoming.\par
  That's the whole thing. Everything else serves that.\par
  ---\par
  The song of every book\par
  Every Mooshu book opens the same way and closes the same way. These are the bookends \emdash  the lullaby shape.\par
  Say them aloud. Soft voice. That's the tempo of the whole series.\par
  ---\par
  The three Mooshus\par
  Three little mushroom-people, stuck above-ground until they find their reason. Each one carries a different shape of the wondering.\par
  Mooshu\par
  Small. A pink-orange cap tilted a bit sideways, too big for her stem, freckled like a quail's egg. She looks like she just got somewhere and already wants to be somewhere else.\par
  Mooshu wants to try everything, in case her reason is hiding in any of it. She starts things and forgets them and remembers them again three breaths later. She says maybe it's this one about almost everything. She's the one who notices the footprint, the fallen feather, the door left open a crack \emdash  but she doesn't always know she's noticing until later.\par
  Her reason, when the forest finally lets her have it: noticing. She's the one who sees what the others miss because she's looking at all of it at once.\par
  Poppen\par
  Taller. A soft tan cap that leans a little to one side, like a hat that's been worn a long time. Quiet eyes. Moves slowly.\par
  Poppen doesn't want to guess wrong. He thinks his one reason is waiting for him somewhere, and he wants to be still enough to hear it arrive. He sits. He watches. When he speaks, the others go quiet, because Poppen doesn't waste words.\par
  His reason: steadying. He's the soft ground the others stand on while they figure themselves out.\par
  Fiddle\par
  A curly little stem, a yellow cap with ragged edges, always mid-motion. Fiddle hums when she's thinking and sings when she isn't.\par
  Fiddle is afraid of being still, because still feels like stuck. So she moves. She tries things. She answers questions before the question is done. She falls over cheerfully and gets back up cheerfully and tries the next thing.\par
  Her reason: beginning. She's the one who goes first, badly and gladly, so the others feel allowed to follow.\par
  The quiet truth underneath\par
  None of them can do their reason alone. Fiddle begins. Mooshu notices. Poppen steadies. That's why they've stayed \emdash  their one thing is each other. But we don't say this out loud in the books. It just slowly becomes true.\par
  ---\par
  Where they live\par
  The Slow Forest. Damp, mossy, full of patches of light that move when the clouds move. Rain every few days, soft.\par
  Three places that come back in every book:\par
  - The Ring \emdash  a circle of old stones where the Mooshus sleep on moss pillows. Home.\par
  - The Edge \emdash  where the forest stops being the forest. Different every book. Something new is always just past the Edge.\par
  - The Old Log \emdash  hollow, mossy, smells like wet bark. Where they go when they feel too small.\par
  ---\par
  The look\par
  A few things that should be true of every page:\par
  - Warm, damp light. The palette is mossy \emdash  greens, soft browns, rain-grey, mushroom-pink, lantern-yellow.\par
  - Hand-painted feel, even if you're working digitally. Visible texture. Nothing too clean.\par
  - The freckles. Every Mooshu has small pale freckles on their cap that glow faintly when they're near their reason. A soft warm glow, not magic-sparkly. If you look closely at every illustration, you can see who's getting warmer. Kids will start hunting for them.\par
  You'll know the style is right when a page feels like it smells like rain.\par
  ---\par
  How every story is shaped\par
  Every Mooshu book moves in the same five soft steps:\par
  1. Morning at the Ring. The opening song. A new day, a little rain, the three of them waking.\par
  2. Something at the Edge. A small thing is a little bit wrong. Often a guest arrives \emdash  a beetle, a seedling, a cricket, a new Mooshu. Nothing scary. Just a small wondering.\par
  3. Each one tries their way. Fiddle rushes. Poppen waits. Mooshu notices. Each of them tries alone, and each of them doesn't quite get there.\par
  4. Together, without planning. The answer shows up when they stop trying separately. Usually they don't even notice they've helped until after.\par
  5. Back to the Ring. The closing song. A little warmer. Freckles glowing a touch brighter than yesterday.\par
  This shape carries as many books as you want to make.\par
  ---\par
  What we don't do\par
  A few quiet rules, so the forest stays the forest:\par
  - No Mooshu ever returns to spores inside these books. Becoming is the point.\par
  - No villains. The trouble is always small, and nothing is ever broken beyond fixing.\par
  - No shouting. No big stakes. No loss.\par
  - Nobody tells a Mooshu what their reason is. They find it by noticing.\par
  - No humans.\par
  - Nobody is ever told they're doing it wrong.\par
  ---\par
  Five books, slowly told\par
  Book one \emdash  Mooshu Wakes Up Wondering\par
  The first one. We meet the three of them, meet the Ring, hear the song for the first time. A small beetle has forgotten which way home is. Fiddle dashes, Poppen waits, Mooshu notices the beetle's own footprints in the moss \emdash  and they follow them backward together. Mooshu's freckles glow a little. Nobody says why.\par
  Book two \emdash  Poppen and the Waiting Tree\par
  A tiny seedling at the Edge is too scared to grow. Fiddle sings to it, which doesn't help. Mooshu notices it's in a cold spot, which helps a little. Poppen sits beside it. Just sits. For a long time. And in the quiet, the seedling decides to come up. Poppen's freckles glow.\par
  Book three \emdash  Fiddle Starts Something\par
  A whole chorus of crickets has gone quiet \emdash  every cricket is waiting for another cricket to go first. Poppen waits with them (this makes it worse). Mooshu notices they're all looking at each other. Fiddle, who cannot stand waiting, chirps \emdash  badly, loudly, gladly \emdash  and the whole forest fills with crickets. Fiddle's freckles glow.\par
  Book four \emdash  The Mooshu Who Tried to Leave\par
  A new Mooshu wakes up at the Edge. Her name is Piko. She thinks she has to find her reason by herself, so she keeps walking away. She tries and tries alone, and gets quieter, and smaller. The three show up beside her without saying anything, and stay. Piko's freckles glow.\par
  This is the tender one. Take care with it.\par
  Book five \emdash  A Little More Knowing\par
  A quiet book. Nothing goes wrong. Mooshu wakes up one morning and realizes she isn't panicked about her reason anymore. The four of them do their things side by side \emdash  Fiddle singing, Mooshu noticing small things, Poppen sitting in the sun, Piko watching it all. The closing song lands differently this time. A whole year of yesterdays.\par
  ---\par
  What to do with this\par
  Read it aloud to each other. Out loud, slowly. Anywhere the words feel like someone else's voice \emdash  change them to yours. This document should sound like you two by the time it's done.\par
  Then read the three names to a few kids. Watch their faces. Keep what lands, rename what doesn't.\par
  Then read the opening song to them. If they repeat "the wonderers" back, you have the series.\par
  1. Book One \emdash  Mooshu Wakes Up Wondering (spread-by-spread)\par
  32 pages. Your girlfriend will want to edit every word \emdash  good. Treat this as the bones, not the final line.\par
  pp 1\endash 2 \'b7 title & copyright\par
  Small vignette: three little freckled caps peeking out of moss in the corner.\par
  pp 3\endash 4 \'b7 dedication spread + opening refrain\par
  Quiet wide image of the Ring at first light, mist curling.\par
  Words:\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Some mushrooms wake up knowing.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Some mushrooms wake up wondering.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The Mooshus are the wonderers.\par
  pp 5\endash 6 \'b7 spread 1 \emdash  morning\par
  The Ring from above. Three sleeping shapes on moss pillows. A soft rain just ending.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The rain had stopped in the night.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The moss was full of it. The stones were shining.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Fiddle opened one eye. Then the other.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Then she sat straight up, because Fiddle is always first.\par
  pp 7\endash 8 \'b7 spread 2 \emdash  waking, together\par
  The three of them. Fiddle already standing, Mooshu blinking, Poppen still curled.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Is it today?" Fiddle said.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Mooshu sat up slowly, freckles soft and dim.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Maybe it's today. Maybe today is the one."\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Poppen didn't open his eyes yet. Poppen was listening.\par
  pp 9\endash 10 \'b7 spread 3 \emdash  a small sound\par
  Close on Poppen's ear-side, eyes now open, head tilted. The forest around them very quiet.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Something is wrong," Poppen said, quietly.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "At the Edge."\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Fiddle was already running.\par
  pp 11\endash 12 \'b7 spread 4 \emdash  the Edge\par
  Wider shot: the Edge of the forest. Ferns, a fallen leaf path. A tiny beetle sitting in the middle of it, looking lost.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  At the Edge of the Slow Forest, a small brown beetle sat\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  in the middle of the path, turning in a slow circle.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "I was going home," said the beetle.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "I was going home, and then I wasn't anymore."\par
  pp 13\endash 14 \'b7 spread 5 \emdash  Fiddle tries\par
  Fiddle in motion, already dashing off into the ferns, hair-leaves flying. The beetle looking after her, puzzled.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "I'll find it!" Fiddle sang, and off she went,\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  one direction, then another, then a third.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  She came back. She hadn't found it.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "But I tried fast," she said, a little smaller.\par
  pp 15\endash 16 \'b7 spread 6 \emdash  Poppen tries\par
  Poppen sitting cross-legged beside the beetle. Both very still. Leaves falling slowly.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "I'll wait," Poppen said.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  He sat beside the beetle and did not move.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The beetle waited with him.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Nothing came.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "I don't think waiting was the thing," Poppen said, soft.\par
  pp 17\endash 18 \'b7 spread 7 \emdash  Mooshu notices\par
  Mooshu crouched, cap tilted, eyes wide. The ground between her and us shows something small the beetle walked through \emdash  tiny footprints in the damp moss.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Mooshu wasn't trying to fix anything yet.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  She was looking at the moss.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Oh," she said.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Oh \emdash  look."\par
  pp 19\endash 20 \'b7 spread 8 \emdash  the footprints\par
  The footprints leading back into the ferns \emdash  very small, very clear. All three Mooshus and the beetle leaning in. Mooshu's freckles glowing, just a little.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Small round prints in the soft wet moss.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  A little trail of where the beetle had been.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "They go back the way you came," said Mooshu.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The beetle looked at Mooshu.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Mooshu looked at her own freckles, which were warm.\par
  pp 21\endash 22 \'b7 spread 9 \emdash  following backward\par
  The four of them walking in a line, following the footprints. Fiddle in front, unable to go slowly, looping around. Poppen at the back, unhurried. Mooshu watching the prints. The beetle looking more hopeful.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  So they followed the footprints backward.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Fiddle went ahead and came back and went ahead.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Poppen came along slowly.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Mooshu watched the moss, and the moss remembered.\par
  pp 23\endash 24 \'b7 spread 10 \emdash  home\par
  A small hollow under a root. Another beetle waiting inside with a tiny crumb. Warm glow from the hollow.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The footprints went to a hollow under a root.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Inside the hollow, another beetle was waiting,\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  with a crumb, and the light on.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "There you are," said the other beetle.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "There I am," said the beetle.\par
  pp 25\endash 26 \'b7 spread 11 \emdash  the walk back\par
  The three Mooshus walking home together through the ferns. Soft light. No words from them yet. Mooshu's freckles a little warmer still.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  The Mooshus walked back toward the Ring.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Nobody said anything for a while.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Fiddle hummed.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Poppen didn't need to.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Mooshu's freckles were warm the whole way.\par
  pp 27\endash 28 \'b7 spread 12 \emdash  back at the Ring, dusk\par
  The Ring at evening, three Mooshus settling back onto their moss pillows. Soft lantern-yellow light in the freckles.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Was that it?" Fiddle asked.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Was that my one thing?"\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  "Maybe a little of it," said Poppen.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Mooshu didn't answer.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  She was already noticing something else.\par
  pp 29\endash 30 \'b7 closing refrain\par
  Wide quiet image: the three of them curled asleep on the moss, freckles softly glowing.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  Not yet. Not yet.\par
  \f1\u9614?\f4  But a little more knowing than yesterday.\par
  pp 31\endash 32 \'b7 about the Mooshus / about us\par
  Tiny author portraits (drawn as mushrooms if you want). A paragraph you two write together, in the same voice.\par
  ---\par
  Word count as written: ~360 words. That's inside the sweet spot. Your girlfriend will cut, reshape, and find a better phrase for half of these \emdash  that's the job. The shape is what matters: each Mooshu gets a\par
  try, Mooshu's try is noticing, the solution is backward through what the beetle already did, and nothing is ever announced.\par
  ---\par
  2. Character visual design prompts (for your sketching)\par
  For each one, sketch 20\endash 30 tiny thumbnails first. Don't polish anything until one shape keeps showing up on its own.\par
  Mooshu\par
  Draw a mushroom who has just realized something interesting three seconds ago and is already forgetting what it was. Her cap is a warm pink-orange, freckled with pale dots like a quail's egg. It sits a\par
  little sideways, like it's grown faster than her stem expected. Her stem is short and a bit round \emdash  not elegant, soft. Her eyes are a size too big for her face and they're always halfway to somewhere else.\par
  Think: the kid at the party who wandered off to look at a cool rock.\par
  When you sketch her, give her motion even when she's still. A cap-tilt, a leaning foot, one hand already pointing at something out of frame. Her freckles are the warmest detail on her \emdash  practice drawing them as tiny soft glows, not sparkles.\par
  Poppen\par
  Draw a mushroom who has been sitting exactly where he is for a long time and is in no hurry. His cap is a soft tan-brown, the color of wet bark in afternoon light, drooping slightly on one side like a hat\par
  worn for years. His stem is taller than Mooshu's and a little thicker, rooted-looking. His eyes are half-closed, not sleepy \emdash  listening. His mouth is usually a small soft line.\par
  When you sketch him, resist the urge to add motion. He's the stillness in the frame. His body language is always vertical and grounded. His freckles are sparser than the others' and harder to see unless you lean in \emdash  just like him.\par
  Fiddle\par
  Draw a mushroom mid-sentence. Bright yellow cap, ragged curly edges like a torn lemon peel, always slightly blurred because she's moving. Her stem is curly and thin, a little wobbly, like a ribbon someone set down and forgot. Her eyes are wide open, eyebrows up, mouth usually open \emdash  singing, asking, about to try. Arms out.\par
  When you sketch her, give her diagonal energy. She's rarely standing straight up. Her freckles are the brightest and most numerous \emdash  scattered all over her cap, and they flicker rather than glow.\par
  The three together\par
  Do a group pose sketch last. The rule: Fiddle is always forward-leaning, Mooshu is always sideways-leaning (looking at something), Poppen is always grounded-vertical. If you can tell who's who by silhouette alone, you've got them.\par
  Environments to sketch next\par
  - The Ring at first light \emdash  a circle of old stones, moss pillows, soft mist, rain-damp. Practice drawing damp.\par
  - The Edge \emdash  ferns, a fallen leaf path. The feeling of something unknown just past the frame.\par
  - The Old Log \emdash  hollow, mossy, warm inside. The refuge.\par
  ---\par
  3. Instagram launch plan (practical mode)\par
  Goal: get to 500 followers before Book 1 releases. 90 days of consistent posting will do it if content is good.\par
  Account setup\par
  - Handle: @mooshubooks (check IG + TikTok + a matching .com)\par
  - Bio: one line of the opening refrain + "a picture-book series by [your names] \'b7 book one coming [month]"\par
  - Link in bio: for now, a simple Carrd.co page (free) with an email signup. When Book 1 launches, swap for the Amazon link + email.\par
  What to post (3\'d7 per week minimum)\par
  Three content pillars, rotate through them:\par
  Pillar 1 \emdash  Process (you):\par
  - Thumbnails, character sketches, color tests, timelapses\par
  - "Meet Mooshu" reveal post, "Meet Poppen," "Meet Fiddle" \emdash  three separate posts, spaced out\par
  - Work-in-progress spread art (even messy)\par
  - Your sketchbook pages\par
  Pillar 2 \emdash  World (her):\par
  - Short voice-over reels of her reading draft lines aloud\par
  - Quiet video of rain + forest with the refrain as text overlay\par
  - Single-line pull quotes from the book on simple mossy backgrounds\par
  - Kid reactions (with parent permission, faces optional) when she reads to them\par
  Pillar 3 \emdash  You two:\par
  - Why you're making it (the belonging theme \emdash  honest, not performative)\par
  - How a caregiver + artist couple works on a book together\par
  - Small authentic moments: "today we disagreed about what color Poppen's cap is"\par
  Cadence template (first 90 days)\par
  - Days 1\endash 7: account setup, post character reveals one at a time (3 posts)\par
  - Weeks 2\endash 4: process content, build the visual world, start the refrain showing up in posts\par
  - Weeks 5\endash 8: introduce the Slow Forest as a place, more reels, first "reading to kids" clip\par
  - Weeks 9\endash 12: Book 1 launch countdown, pre-order/email signup push, cover reveal, first-look spread\par
  The few rules that matter\par
  - Post from the world, not about the business. Never post about "building a brand." Post from inside the forest.\par
  - Use the refrain as a closing line on posts. Repetition is branding. "Not yet. Not yet." should show up often.\par
  - Reels over photos. IG/TikTok push video hard. Even slow pans of sketches with ambient forest sound perform well.\par
  - Engage small accounts back. Follow & reply to other indie kidlit makers, caregivers, ADHD/neurodivergent parent accounts. That's where your first 500 live.\par
  - Don't buy followers or use generic hashtags. Use a tight set: #kidlit #picturebook #indiepicturebook #selfpublishing #kdp #illustratorsofinstagram #mushroomart #neurodivergentkids\par
  What to track\par
  - Followers (loose proxy)\par
  - Email signups on the Carrd page (the real number that matters)\par
  - Which post types get saved/shared the most \emdash  that's your signal\par
  ---\par
  Three things to decide together this week, before anything else:\par
  1. Is the Book 1 word count and shape right, or do you want it longer/shorter?\par
  2. Pick the trim size (8.5\'d78.5 square vs 8\'d710 portrait) \emdash  changes all your thumbnails\par
  3. Claim the @mooshubooks handles tonight before someone else does\par
