\par
\b The Mooshu Writer's Companion\b0\par
\par
  A small book about how to make more of them. Not rules you have to obey \emdash  shapes you can lean on when the next book won't come.\par
\par
  ---\par
  1. How to start a new book\par
\par
  Every Mooshu story starts the same way: not with a plot, with a visitor.\par
\par
  A small someone arrives at the Edge of the Slow Forest carrying one small feeling. That's your whole seed. You don't need a story yet. You need a guest, and the guest brings the weather.\par
\par
  So the process is:\par
\par
  Step one \emdash  pick a feeling. One small, specific one. Not ready. Too fast. Carrying too much. Missed the beginning. Came back different. (There's a list further down if you're stuck.)\par
\par
  Step two \emdash  pick a guest who carries it. Not their species or name yet \emdash  their shape. A creature who has just lost something, or just arrived somewhere, or just noticed something nobody else has. (Archetype\par
  list further down too.)\par
\par
  Step three \emdash  put them at the Edge. Morning at the Ring. The guest is there when the Mooshus wake, or arrives after breakfast, or is standing very still on the leaf-path. The guest doesn't know what they\par
  need. Neither do the Mooshus. That's fine.\par
\par
  Step four \emdash  let each Mooshu try their way. Fiddle will begin. Poppen will wait. Mooshu will notice. Each of them tries alone. Each of them doesn't quite get there. This is the shape of every book and it\par
  never gets old if the feeling underneath is specific.\par
\par
  Step five \emdash  the together-answer. The three of them solve it without meaning to, usually by combining their instincts in a small accidental way. They don't plan it. They just do it, and afterward it's done.\par
\par
  Step six \emdash  read it aloud. Not to yourselves. To actual kids. The book isn't real yet. Kids will tell you what's real by what they repeat back and what they ignore.\par
\par
  ---\par
  2. Feelings to build books around\par
\par
  Kid-sized feelings are small and specific. "Sad" is not a book. "I thought I remembered the way and then I didn't" is a book.\par
\par
  Some to work from:\par
\par
  - I showed up and nobody was ready for me\par
  - I was ready and nobody showed up\par
  - I have too much to carry and can't put any of it down\par
  - I started something and can't remember why\par
  - I finished something and don't know what's next\par
  - I'm doing it wrong but I don't know what right looks like\par
  - I said the thing and it came out wrong\par
  - Someone changed and I don't know them the same way\par
  - I'm waiting and the waiting feels like forever\par
  - I went looking and forgot what I was looking for\par
  - Everyone else already knows the song\par
  - I am too fast for here\par
  - I am too slow for here\par
  - I am in the wrong shape\par
  - I am in the right shape but the wrong place\par
  - I used to know and then I didn't\par
  - I tried and nothing happened\par
  - I didn't try and something happened anyway\par
  - Someone small needs me and I don't know how\par
  - I miss something that isn't gone yet\par
\par
  Any one of these can be a Mooshu book. Write the feeling on an index card. Pin it up. The story will come.\par
\par
  ---\par
  3. Guest character archetypes\par
\par
  You'll do the naming, the species, the look. These are just the shapes to pick from. Each one generates many stories.\par
\par
  The one who's running late. Arrives out of breath. Thinks they've missed everything. They haven't \emdash  nothing has started yet.\par
\par
  The one who got there too early. Has been waiting a long time. Has started to wonder if they dreamed the invitation.\par
\par
  The one who's carrying something heavy. A stick too big for them, a secret, a grudge, a memory. Won't set it down even when offered help.\par
\par
  The one who forgot the way. Knew it once. The path has changed, or they have.\par
\par
  The one who's the wrong size for their job. Too small for the task, or too big for the space. Trying anyway.\par
\par
  The one who's waiting for permission. Ready to go. Standing at the edge of going. Nobody has told them they can.\par
\par
  The one who showed up uninvited. Not sure if they're welcome. Trying to be as quiet as possible about it.\par
\par
  The one who came back changed. Was here before. Left. Came back. The forest remembers them as they used to be.\par
\par
  The one whose rhythm doesn't fit. Moves faster or slower than the forest. Keeps bumping into the tempo.\par
\par
  The one who traded something and misses it. Gave up something small to get something else. The something else isn't enough anymore.\par
\par
  The one who's looking for a specific someone. Won't say who. Asks careful, hopeful questions.\par
\par
  The one who doesn't want to be found. Tucked into the moss. Might want company, might not. Hard to tell.\par
\par
  The one who keeps apologizing. For everything. Especially for small things that didn't need apologizing for.\par
\par
  The one who's too full of something to speak. Joy, grief, a song, a secret. Hums but doesn't say.\par
\par
  The one who made a tiny mistake and can't let it go. Dropped something. Stepped on something. Small, undone, still heavy.\par
\par
  The one who showed someone the way once and is tired now. Has been the guide for too long. Doesn't know how to stop being the guide.\par
\par
  The one who's the first of their kind here. Doesn't know if they belong. Nobody has told them otherwise.\par
\par
  The one who keeps almost-starting. Has been about to begin for a long time. Beginning is hard.\par
\par
  The one who lost the word for something. Knows the thing. Can't name it. The word is in the forest somewhere.\par
\par
  The one who's trying to give something away. Has something to give. Can't find who it's for.\par
\par
  Pair any one of these with a feeling from the list above and you have a book.\par
\par
  ---\par
  4. Prompts when you're stuck\par
\par
  Fill in the blanks. Read the filled sentence aloud. If it makes you want to draw, it's a book.\par
\par
  - A ______ arrives at the Edge, carrying a ______ they can't put down.\par
  - Something small at the Ring is ______ today, and nobody knows why.\par
  - A guest has been waiting at the Old Log for ______, and doesn't remember ______.\par
  - Today the rain didn't come, and ______.\par
  - A new Mooshu wakes up and thinks their one thing is ______. It isn't.\par
  - The forest is quieter than usual because ______.\par
  - A ______ has come to say goodbye to ______ before ______.\par
  - Fiddle tried to start the day and it ______. Poppen tried to steady it and it ______. Mooshu noticed ______.\par
\par
  ---\par
  5. Deeper patterns (craft rules, earned the hard way)\par
\par
  A few things that will save you when a book feels wrong.\par
\par
  The guest is the theme. Not the Mooshus. The Mooshus are constant. The guest brings this book's feeling. If you can't describe your guest in one emotion, you don't have a book yet.\par
\par
  Show the feeling through a small physical thing. Not "the beetle was sad" \emdash  "the beetle sat in the middle of the path, turning in a slow circle." The picture is the feeling. Always.\par
\par
  Each Mooshu tries exactly once, in order of their instinct. Fiddle, Poppen, Mooshu. Not twice. Not in a different order. The rhythm is the ritual.\par
\par
  Never announce the resolution. The answer just happens. The Mooshus don't explain that they solved it together. A kid who's been read the book three times will figure it out on their own, and that moment of\par
  figuring is the gift.\par
\par
  The freckles do the saying-without-saying. Whose freckles glow at the end is your theme-signal. Don't overuse \emdash  sometimes all three glow a little, sometimes only the one whose instinct was the key that time.\par
   Vary it.\par
\par
  The closing refrain has to land differently each book, without changing. Same words, different weight. Book 1's "not yet" feels like starting. Book 10's feels like trust. That's the whole magic of a refrain.\par
\par
  If a line explains the lesson, cut it. Toddlers don't need the lesson. They need the feeling. The parent reading aloud is the one who will feel the lesson, once, and quietly.\par
\par
  Nothing in the Slow Forest is ever fixed, only accompanied. The Mooshus don't solve the guest's problem. They're with them while the problem solves itself, or doesn't, or changes shape. This is the deepest\par
  rule. Break it and the series stops being itself.\par
\par
  Write short. Cut shorter. 300\endash 450 words per book. A word you love that isn't working is the first one to go.\par
\par
  Read every draft aloud three times: once to your girlfriend, once to a kid, once in your own head at night. If any of those readings stumbles on the same line, rewrite that line.\par
\par
  ---\par
  6. How to extend past five books\par
\par
  Once the first arc is done, the series has three ways to grow without breaking:\par
\par
  New Mooshus wake up. Piko joined in Book 4. More can come. Each new Mooshu brings a new shape of stuck \emdash  a new way of not knowing. But keep the core trio central; new Mooshus are guests-who-stayed, not\par
  replacements.\par
\par
  The forest opens. New locations past the Edge. A meadow. A stream. A hollow tree. Each new place is its own small world with its own small rules. Go slow \emdash  one new place every few books.\par
\par
  The seasons deepen. Same forest, different weather. A winter book. A long-rain book. A hot-still-afternoon book. Season books let you tell quieter stories where the guest is the weather itself.\par
\par
  What not to do:\par
  - Don't give the Mooshus powers. They find their reasons by noticing, not by growing stronger.\par
  - Don't add stakes. The forest stays small and safe. The feelings are the stakes.\par
  - Don't add grown-ups. No human parents, no wise old figures who explain things.\par
  - Don't solve belonging. The Mooshus belong to each other and to the wondering. They never graduate.\par
\par
  ---\par
  7. A small ritual for writing days\par
\par
  Before you write a new book, the two of you:\par
\par
  1. Sit down together with no screen.\par
  2. Pick one feeling card and one archetype card (you can literally make the cards).\par
  3. Say the opening refrain aloud together.\par
  4. Spend ten minutes describing the guest to each other out loud \emdash  what they're carrying, why they're at the Edge, what they don't yet know they need.\par
  5. Then open the document.\par
\par
  The forest is slow. Your process can be too.\f0\lang9\par
}
